<paper id="1957550856"><title>Temporal Logic and Causality in Concurrent Systems</title><year>1988</year><authors><author org="GMD, St. Augustin, W. Germany#TAB#" id="531013306">Wolfgang Reisig</author></authors><n_citation>27</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>59246472</reference><reference>1503002024</reference><reference>1524991160</reference><reference>1600408058</reference><reference>1991052229</reference><reference>2030926579</reference><reference>2031145943</reference><reference>2040127143</reference><reference>2048355938</reference><reference>2066612386</reference></references><venue id="1145706541" type="C">International Conference on Concurrency Theory</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-50403-6_37</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.65088">Computation tree logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.72066">Temporal logic of actions</keyword><keyword weight="0.6801">Interval temporal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.44385">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.67769">Concurrency</keyword><keyword weight="0.68357">Multimodal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.45361">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.71044">Linear temporal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.62395">Modal logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.68816">Temporal logic</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A logic is introduced, tailored for causality based partial order semantics of non-sequential systems. Properties which are essential for such systems can be formulated in the logic. Technically, the system model we consider is the most fundamental version of Petri Nets. We study a logic for detached runs, which resembles the purposes of Linear Time Temporal Logic for Interleavings.</abstract></paper>